e 1:\n\n\nInput: position = [1,2,3]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: First step: Move the chip at position 3 to position 1 with cost = 0.\nSecond step: Move the chip at position 2 to position 1 with cost = 1.\nTotal cost is 1.\n\nExample 2:\n\n\nInput: position = [2,2,2,3,3]\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: We can move the two chips at position  3 to position 2. Each move has cost = 1. The total cost = 2.\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: position = [1,1000000000]\nOutput: 1\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= position.length <= 100\n1 <= position[i] <= 10^9\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minCostToMoveChips(self, position: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minCostToMoveChips(self, position: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Count the number of chips at even and odd positions\n        even_count = sum(1 for pos in position if pos % 2 == 0)\n        odd_count = sum(1 for pos in position if pos % 2 != 0)\n        \n        # The minimum cost will be the smaller count because moving chips between even positions or odd positions is free\n        return min(even_count, odd_count)\n```\n\nThis solution leverages the fact that moving chips between even positions or between odd positions incurs no cost. Therefore, the problem reduces to counting how many chips are in even positions and how many are in odd positions. The minimum cost to move all chips to the same position will be the smaller of these two counts, as you can move all chips to the parity (even or odd) with the smaller count at a cost of 1 per chip.", "estimated_date": 1570320000000}